	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Montreal</placeName> <date>22d Novr 5619</date></p>
				<p><addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">You could not<lb/> have received any request to<lb/> discontinue sending the Occident<lb/> to <persName>Mr Brahadi</persName> who had refused<lb/> it at the Post Office&#8212;and as he<lb/> says directed the clerk to take the<lb/> usual course of informing the<lb/> Editor per printed slip of the same.<lb/>  I have endeavored to persuade<lb/> him to continue it&#8212;but the<lb/> only reply I got was he would<lb/> also discontinue the Jewish messenger<lb/> which it seems was sent him<lb/> without his request.  He is<lb/> a London Chronicle man.  Don&#39;t<lb/> be offended however.  The Israelite<lb/> only circulates one copy here</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>the one received by your humble<lb/> servant&#8212;and it is supplied me<lb/> for considerably less than three<lb/> Dollars per annum so neither<lb/> <persName>Wise</persName> nor <persName>Gluck</persName> will ride in<lb/> a carriage from their <placeName>Montreal</placeName><lb/> income.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Are you going to complete<lb/> the Translation of my fathers<lb/> <persName>Reggio</persName>&#63;  Is there no Dutchman<lb/> at hand yet&#63;  My father writes me <persName>Mr<lb/> Gershom Kursheedt</persName> has secured<lb/> the rare copy of <add>Hebrew</add> of which<lb/> I wrote you&#8212;and apropos<lb/> des <hi rend="underline">battes</hi> <persName>Dr Lowe</persName> writes me<lb/> he is going to send me a copy of<lb/> his Circassion<add>&#63;</add> &#38; Turkish Dictionary<lb/>&#8212;I have <add>&#63;</add> <persName>David</persName>&#44; and have<lb/> a smattering of Arabic&#59; but I<lb/> hardly think am Turk enough<lb/> to give an opinion of the learned<lb/> Doctors work.  It is gratifying</p>
			<pb n="3"/>
				<p>to have such a man amongst us.<lb/>  His work has been published at<lb/> the expense of the London Philological<lb/> Society.  He is also going to send me<lb/> some other of his works published<lb/> by the London Humanistic Society<lb/> more notice should be taken of<lb/> him in the London Chronicle.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Dr Dawson</persName> the Principal<lb/> of Mc Gill College&#8212;a man of<lb/> great endowments and deep learning<lb/> favorably known in the <placeName>United States</placeName><lb/> and <placeName>Europe</placeName> as one of the greatest<lb/> geologists of the day&#8212;especially<lb/> for his studies of the Carboniferous<lb/> Flora&#8212;is about publishing<lb/> a work called Archaia&#8212;wherein<lb/> he considers the alleged discrepancies<lb/> between the Mosaic &#38; Geological<lb/> accounts of the Cosmogony&#8212;<lb/>as well as the origin of the human<lb/> race.  As <persName>Dr D.</persName> is celebrated as<lb/> a man of science&#44; and he will</p>
			<pb n="4"/>
				<p>write in a reverent spirit&#44; the<lb/> work is not less interesting to us<lb/> than to Christians.  I would like<lb/> you to see it.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I require a couple of<lb/> numbers of the Occident to complete<lb/> my file.  As <persName>Sarah Joseph</persName>&#8212;who<lb/> takes this for me&#8212;is going to<lb/> make some stay in your city<lb/> You can send them to me by her.<lb/>  If I have time before the <add>&#63;</add><lb/> I will see which are the missing<lb/> nos.  I think I want Nos 1. &#38; 2<lb/> in vol XIV&#8212;but I will write<lb/> you again.  Meanwhile I am Yours Truly</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)"><persName role="author">Abraham de Sola</persName></p>
		</body>
